  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum of 30 years if the laundering involves proceeds from certain specified unlawful activities\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential civil monetary penalties\n\n3. Asset forfeiture:\n- Government can seize assets involved in or derived from money laundering transactions\n\n4. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Reputational damage\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Nature of underlying criminal activity\n- Individual's criminal history\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n\nProsecutions typically occur under statutes like:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\nThese are general legal guidelines. For precise details about a specific situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
